# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-spanish-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] A general election was held in Spain on 27 April 1884 (for the Congress of Deputies) and on 8 May 1884 (for the Senate), to elect the members of the 3rd Cortes under the Spanish Constitution of 1876, during the Restoration period.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] All 433 seats in the Congress of Deputies were up for election, as well as 180 of 360 seats in the Senate.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The monarch would play a key role in the *turno* system by appointing and dismissing governments, which would then organize elections to provide themselves with a parliamentary majority.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Under the 1876 Constitution, the Spanish Cortes were conceived as "co-legislative bodies", forming a nearly perfect bicameral system.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The term of each chamber of the Cortes—the Congress and one-half of the elective part of the Senate—expired five years from the date of their previous election, unless they were dissolved earlier.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The previous elections were held on 21 August 1881 for the Congress and on 2 September 1881 for the Senate, which meant that the chambers' terms would have expired on 21 August and 2 September 1886, respectively.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The monarch had the prerogative to dissolve both chambers at any given time—either jointly or separately—and call a snap election.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] There was no constitutional requirement for concurrent elections to the Congress and the Senate, nor for the elective part of the Senate to be renewed in its entirety except in the case that a full dissolution was agreed by the monarch.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Still, there was only one case of a separate election (for the Senate in 1877) and no half-Senate elections taking place under the 1876 Constitution.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The Cortes were officially dissolved on 31 March 1884, with the corresponding decree setting election day for 27 April (Congress) and 8 May 1884 (Senate) and scheduling for both chambers to reconvene on 20 May.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] In the Spanish West Indies (Cuba and Puerto Rico) the taxpayer requirement was higher (Pts 125, or $25), while former Cuban slaves were barred from voting until three years after becoming freedmen.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] In the Basque Provinces and Navarre—where taxes were not paid directly—voters had instead to prove wealth equivalent to an income of Pts 4,800; or Pts 2,400 in real estate, crops or livestock.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Additional restrictions excluded those deprived of political rights or barred from public office by a final sentence, criminally imprisoned or convicted, legally incapacitated, bankrupt, and public debtors.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The Congress of Deputies had one seat per 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The remaining seats were elected in single-member districts by plurality voting and distributed among the provinces of Spain according to population.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Up to 10 additional members could be elected through cumulative voting if they ran in several single-member districts and obtained over 10,000 votes overall.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Cuba and Puerto Rico were allocated 24 and 15 seats, respectively.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] 180 Senate seats were elected using indirect, two-round majority voting.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Delegates chosen by local councils—each of which was assigned an initial minimum of one delegate, with one additional delegate for every six councillors—voted for senators together with provincial deputies.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The remaining 33 seats were allocated to special institutional districts (one each), including major archdioceses, royal academies, universities, and economic societies, each elected by their own qualified electors or delegates.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] The law provided for by-elections to fill vacant seats during the legislative term.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] At least two vacancies were required to trigger a by-election in Congress multi-member constituencies; when only two vacancies were to be filled, voters could choose only one candidate.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] For the Congress, secular Spanish males of voting age, with full civil rights, could run for election.
[src:1884-spanish-general-election/1884-spanish-general-election] Other ineligibility provisions for the Senate also applied to a number of territorial officials within their areas of jurisdiction, during their term of office and up to three months afterwards; public contractors; tax collectors; and public debtors.
